#MEM id=examples source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Finance/felix/skills/executive-operations/saas-revenue-growth-metrics/examples/healthy-saas.md
M|examples|**Company:** ProjectHub (mid-market project management SaaS)
M|examples|**Stage:** Growth stage, Series B funded
M|examples|**Customer Base:** 200 accounts, 20,000 users
M|examples|**Period:** Monthly snapshot
M|examples|```
M|examples|Starting MRR: $2,000,000
M|examples|+ New MRR: $100,000 (10 new accounts)
M|examples|+ Expansion MRR: $80,000 (upsells + usage growth)
M|examples|- Churned MRR: $30,000 (5 accounts churned)
M|examples|- Contraction MRR: $10,000 (3 accounts downgraded)
M|examples|Ending MRR: $2,140,000
M|examples|MRR Growth Rate: 7% MoM
M|examples|ARR: $25.7M
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|ARPA = $2,140,000 / 200 accounts = $10,700/month
M|examples|ARPU = $2,140,000 / 20,000 users = $107/month
M|examples|Average seats per account = 100 users
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|New MRR: $100K (5% of total)
M|examples|Expansion MRR: $80K (4% of total)
M|examples|Churned MRR: $30K (1.5% of total)
M|examples|Contraction MRR: $10K (0.5% of total)
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|Logo Churn: 5 / 200 = 2.5% monthly (~26% annual)
M|examples|Revenue Churn: $30K / $2M = 1.5% monthly (~17% annual)
M|examples|```
M|examples|**Analysis:** Revenue churn < logo churn = losing smaller customers, which is healthy.
M|examples|```
M|examples|Starting ARR: $24M
M|examples|Expansion: $960K (annual)
M|examples|Churned: $360K (annual)
M|examples|Contraction: $120K (annual)
M|examples|Ending ARR: $24.48M
M|examples|NRR = $24.48M / $24M = 102%
M|examples|```
M|examples|```
M|examples|Gains = $100K + $80K = $180K
M|examples|Losses = $30K + $10K = $40K
M|examples|Quick Ratio = $180K / $40K = 4.5
M|examples|```
M|examples|**Strong growth:**
M|examples|- 7% MoM MRR growth
M|examples|- Healthy mix: 5% new + 4% expansion
M|examples|**Excellent retention:**
M|examples|- 2.5% logo churn (below 5% threshold)
M|examples|- 1.5% revenue churn (better than logo)
M|examples|- 102% NRR (growing without new logos)
M|examples|**Efficient expansion:**
M|examples|- $80K expansion MRR (4% of base)
M|examples|- Expansion-driven NRR
M|examples|- Average expansion per account: $400/month
M|examples|**Sustainable growth:**
M|examples|- Quick Ratio 4.5 (gains far exceed losses)
M|examples|- Revenue churn declining (was 2% six months ago)
M|examples|- Newer cohorts retain better than older cohorts
M|examples|**Expansion room:**
M|examples|- NRR at 102% is good, but room to grow to 110-120%
M|examples|- Only 40% of customers have expanded (could push to 60%)
M|examples|- Cross-sell opportunity: 30% of customers don't use integrations add-on
M|examples|**ARPU optimization:**
M|examples|- $107/user is solid for mid-market, but enterprise segment shows $200/user potential
M|examples|- Could introduce premium tier for advanced features
M|examples|**Reduce churn:**
M|examples|- 2.5% logo churn is acceptable but not excellent
M|examples|- Analysis shows 70% of churn happens in first 90 days (onboarding problem)
M|examples|- Fix: Improve onboarding, aim for <2% logo churn
M|examples|1. **Scale acquisition aggressively** — Unit economics are strong (see `saas-economics-efficiency-metrics` for CAC/LTV)
M|examples|2. **Improve onboarding** — Reduce early churn from 5% to 3% in first 90 days
M|examples|3. **Expand cross-sell** — Push integrations add-on to 30% of base without it (potential +$30K MRR)
M|examples|4. **Test premium tier** — 20 enterprise customers show willingness to pay 2x for advanced features
M|examples|5. **Monitor cohort retention** — Continue tracking that new cohorts retain better than old
M|examples|| Cohort | Month 6 Retention | Month 12 Retention |
M|examples||--------|-------------------|---------------------|
M|examples|| 12 months ago | 85% | 78% |
M|examples|| 6 months ago | 88% | TBD |
M|examples|| Current | 92% (on track) | TBD |
M|examples|**Analysis:** Newer cohorts retaining better = product improvements working. Safe to scale acquisition.